05379nam a22009255i 9781501502149DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20152015gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2015019801  a(OCoLC)979781200  a97815015021497 a10.1515/97815015021492doi  a(DE-B1597)448844  a(OCoLC)917873529  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aP95.54b.B36 2015 7aLAN0090002bisacsh1 aBaker, Will, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCulture and Identity through English as a Lingua Franca :bRethinking Concepts and Goals in Intercultural Communication /cWill Baker. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (284 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDevelopments in English as a Lingua Franca [DELF] ,x2192-8177 ;v800tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tTable of contents -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2. Intercultural communication and ELF -- tChapter 3. Understanding culture through ELF -- tChapter 4. Culture and identity through English as a lingua franca -- tChapter 5. Re-examining intercultural communicative competence: intercultural awareness -- tChapter 6. ELF and intercultural awareness: implications for English language teaching -- tChapter 7. Putting it into practice: A study of a course in ELF and ICA for language learners in Thailand -- tChapter 8. Conclusion -- tAppendices -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe use of English as a global lingua franca has given rise to new challenges and approaches in our understanding of language and communication. One area where ELF (English as a lingua franca) studies, both from an empirical and theoretical orientation, have the potential for significant developments is in our understanding of the relationships between language, culture and identity. ELF challenges traditional assumptions concerning the purposed 'inexorable' link between a language and a culture. Due to the multitude of users and contexts of ELF communication the supposed language, culture and identity correlation, often conceived at the national level, appears simplistic and naïve. However, it is equally naïve to assume that ELF is a culturally and identity neutral form of communication. All communication involves participants, purposes, contexts and histories, none of which are 'neutral'. Thus, we need new approaches to understanding the relationship between language, culture and identity which are able to account for the multifarious and dynamic nature of ELF communication.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aEnglish languagexForeign countries. 0aEnglish languagexSocial aspects. 0aEnglish languagezForeign countries. 0aIdentity (Philosophical concept)xSocial aspects. 0aIntercultural communicationxSocial aspects. 0aLingua francas. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aCulture.  aEducation.  aEnglish as a Lingua Franca.  aIdentity.  aIntercultural Communication.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2015 Part 1z978311076251808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter Mouton Backlist 2000-2015z978311074296108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2015z9783110438710oZDB-23-DSP0 cEPUBz97815015021630 cprintz978150151062540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150150214940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501502149423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9